Wait, the Java code for that part is:

if (N - k * (A + B) > A) {
    System.out.println(A * k + (N - k * (A + B)) - (N - (k * (A + B) + A)));
} else {
    System.out.println(A * k + (N - k * (A + B)));
}

Let me compute that subtraction part.

Otherwise, output N. Because if A is larger than N, you can't have more than N blue balls. So min(A, N) in that case. But in Fortran, the else if condition would be (A + B > N) then, but inside that, check if A <= N.

So putting it all together. But the original Java code's structure is:

if (A + B <= N) {
    ... compute k, rem, etc.
} else if (A + B > N && A <= N) {
    output A
} else {
    output N
} So in Fortran, the structure would be:

if (A_plus_B <= N) then
    ... 
else
    if (A <= N) then
        print A
    else
        print N
    end if
end if

Because when A_plus_B > N, then the code checks if A is <= N. If so, output A. Otherwise, output N. So if A_plus_B > N, then we can only have up to min(A, N) blue balls.
